<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,369,151,177]" box="[151,369,151,177]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,369,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Hood" authorityName="Hood" box="[151,369,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Plesiothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,369,151,177]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Plesiothrips</emphasis>
Hood
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,222,463]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
A total of 
<number box="[264,292,222,246]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="19.0">19</number>
species are currently listed in this genus. Of these, five are from Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1169,1228,222,246]" name="United States of America" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">USA</collectingCountry>
, and the others are all Neotropical with the exception of 
<taxonomicName box="[568,711,259,283]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Plesiothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sakagamii">
<emphasis box="[568,711,259,283]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">P. sakagamii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described on three females from 
<collectingCountry box="[1085,1171,258,282]" name="Taiwan" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
. However, there is little in the description of that species to distinguish it from 
<taxonomicName box="[783,922,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Plesiothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis box="[783,922,294,319]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">P. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species that is widespread among tropical countries and is variable in colour and chaetotaxy. This species has been taken across northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1212,1315,330,354]" name="Australia" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Australia</collectingCountry>
from various introduced grasses and also 
<taxonomicName box="[513,620,368,391]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Zea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mays">
<emphasis box="[513,620,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Zea mays</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There are no published studies on the breeding habits of this thrips, but the ovipositor is too weak and non-serrate to be effective in inserting eggs into plant tissues, suggesting the possibility that the eggs of this thrips are placed within the glumes of florets.
</paragraph>
